    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1972-11-27T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1972-11-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="137"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d137">
                <head>137. Memorandum from Secretary <persName corresp="#p_RWP1" type="from"
                        >Rogers</persName> to President <persName corresp="#p_NRM1" type="to"
                        >Nixon</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d137fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, President’s Evening Reading: Lot 74 D
                        164. Confidential.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d137fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWP1">Rogers</persName> informed the President of
                        details of the first Swiss-Cuban meeting on the proposed Cuban Hijacking
                        Agreement.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1972-11-27"
                        >November 27, 1972</date>.</dateline>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="underline">MEMORANDUM FOR THE PRESIDENT</hi> - Evening Report</p>
                <p>Cuban Proposal for Hijacking Agreement - We have received a report of the first
                    Swiss-Cuban meeting on a hijacking agreement which took place in Havana
                    Saturday. The Cuban side tabled a draft agreement which provides for stiff
                    punishment by the receiving country of persons who seize or divert planes or
                    vessels. Return of the offenders is neither required nor referred to. The
                    obligation of prosecution does not apply in the case of political asylum, which
                    is very narrowly defined. The Cuban draft also contemplates punishment by each
                    party of persons who use its territory to prepare or carry out acts of violence
                    against the territory of the other party or aircraft or vessels going to or from
                    the other party’s territory. With respect to refugees, it merely provides that
                    each country will apply its own laws strictly to persons coming from the
                    territory of the other party.</p>
                <p>The Cuban proposal appears somewhat more acceptable than the Cuban position in
                    1969-70 on this subject. We tentatively plan to use it as a framework for
                    further Swiss-Cuban discussion and are considering proposing various amendments
                    to it for the next meeting.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWP1">William P. Rogers</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
